To create a TikZ diagram that visually represents the arrangement of image sources for a Casimir system with the given conditions, you can use the following code:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3]
    % Draw the plates
    \draw[thick] (-1, -0.5) rectangle (1, 0.5);
    \draw[thick] (-1, 1.5) rectangle (1, 2.5);

    % Draw the image sources
    \foreach \n in {-4,-3,...,3,4} {
        \fill[black] (\n, -0.5) circle (0.05); % Left plate
        \fill[black] (\n, 2.5) circle (0.05); % Right plate
    }

    % Draw the z-axis line
    \draw[dashed, thick] (0, -0.5) -- (0, 2.5);
    \node at (0, 2.7) {$z$};

    % Label the plates
    \node at (-1.5, -0.8) {Left Plate};
    \node at (-1.5, 2.8) {Right Plate};

    % Add annotations
    \node at (-3, -0.5) [below right] {Image Sources};
    \node at (3, 2.5) [above left] {Image Sources};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

This code will generate a TikZ diagram showing two parallel plates with image sources placed at intervals of \(a\) along the \(z\)-axis. The image sources are labeled as black dots on both plates. The dashed line indicates the \(z\)-axis, and labels are provided for clarity.

If you need further customization or additional details, feel free to ask!

